          "body": "Psalm 13 does not quote the New Testament, but the New Testament breathes its air. The cry 'How long will You hide Your face from me?' (13:1) finds its deepest fulfillment in the cry of the Son of David from the cross: 'My God, My God, why have You forsaken Me?' (Matthew 27:46; Psalm 22:1). Jesus did not merely identify with the suffering psalmists — He became the ultimate sufferer of divine hiddenness, the one from whom the Father's face was actually withdrawn in the moment of sin-bearing. If Psalm 13 is the lament of a covenant servant experiencing God's hiddenness, Calvary is its fullest realization — and Easter is the answer to every 'how long' ever prayed. Tim Keller (*The Songs of Jesus*, 2015) observes that Jesus prayed these psalms as a Jew and then fulfilled them as the Son of God. The believer who prays Psalm 13 prays it, in Christ, with the resurrection already behind them — which is exactly the logic David himself anticipates in verse 5: praising before the rescue, because the rescuer's character is known."
